  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the issues with the new Royal Enfield Himalayan?",
  "response": "The new Royal Enfield Himalayan, while well-received by many, has faced some criticisms and issues that potential buyers should be aware of. Here are some of the common concerns raised by riders and reviewers:\n\n1. **Build Quality and Reliability:**\n   - Some users have reported issues with the build quality, such as loose fittings and rattles, which can affect the overall riding experience.\n   - There have been occasional reports of electrical issues, including problems with the wiring harness and lights.\n\n2. **Engine Performance:**\n   - The new 452cc engine, while an improvement over the older model, has been noted for its lack of low-end torque. Some riders feel the bike struggles at low speeds and in traffic.\n   - The engine can get hot, especially during long rides in traffic, which may affect comfort.\n\n3. **Suspension and Handling:**\n   - The suspension setup has been criticized for being too soft, which can lead to a less stable ride on rough terrains and at higher speeds.\n   - Some riders have reported that the bike feels top-heavy, affecting its maneuverability in tight spaces.\n\n4. **Braking System:**\n   - The braking system, while adequate, has been noted for its lack of bite, especially in wet conditions. Some riders feel that the ABS settings could be improved for better performance.\n\n5. **Ergonomics and Comfort:**\n   - While the seating position is generally praised for long-distance comfort, some riders have found the seat to be too firm, leading to discomfort on extended rides.\n   - The placement of the controls and switches has been criticized by some for being less intuitive than desired.\n\n6. **Price and Value:**\n   - The new Himalayan comes at a higher price point than its predecessor, which has led some to question its value for money, especially when compared to other adventure bikes in the market.\n\n7. **Fuel Efficiency:**\n   - While the new model offers good fuel efficiency, some users have reported that it falls short of the manufacturer's claimed figures, particularly during aggressive riding.\n\n8. **After-Sales Service:**\n   - There have been mixed reviews about the after-sales service and availability of spare parts, which can be a concern for long-term ownership.\n\nIt's important to note that these issues may vary from one rider to another, and some might not experience these problems at all. Potential buyers are encouraged to take a test ride and do thorough research to see if the new Royal Enfield Himalayan meets their needs and expectations.",
